VINCULOS.OUTRAS-INFORMACOES: Obtive uma bolsa de Pós-Doutorado pela Fundação de Amparo a Pesquisa do Estado de São Paulo (FAPESP) com o tı́tulo Desenvolvimento do código MCMC/MCEF para o estudo de reações do tipo spallation e sua aplicação em Reatores Hbridos. O estudo da fsica da reação de espalação foi aprofundada com a implementação dos processos envolvidos, como por exemplo, interação de um feixe de prótons através de modelos fı́sicos mais realistas. Este modelo foi desenvolvido e implementado em um programa de Monte Carlo ?CRISP? com o objetivo de se estudar os processos fsicos envolvidos, principalmente em relação à multiplicidade de nêutrons, caracterı́stica muito importante quando se projeta um reator hı́brido para geração de energia. O código CRISP (Colaboração Rio Ilhéus São Paulo) consiste em dois blocos - um Monte Carlo Multi-Colisional (MCMC) e um Monte Carlo para Evaporação Fissão (MCEF). O primeiro descreve o processo e cascata intranuclear, enquanto o segundo é dedicado a fase de evaporação - fissão . Ambos os códigos têm se mostrado muito eficientes no cálculo de inmeros processos nucleares. O código CRISP também se mostra eficiente em outras áreas e aplicações , como fsica de hádrons, reações nucleares especficas, processos de espalação ou fissão iniciados com diferentes feixes, e muitas outras. LINHA-DE-PESQUISA.OBJETIVOS-LINHA-DE-PESQUISA:
Neste trabalho, foram introduzidas várias mudanças no conceito originalmente proposto por Carlo Rubbia[1] como, por exemplo, mais de um ponto de espalação para se reduzir a energia e a corrente exigidas pelo acelerador e também se obter um fluxo de nêutrons mais uniforme. O núcleo sub-crı́tico, que na proposta original era um arranjo hexagonal de varetas imerso em chumbo lı́quido foi substituido por uma calândria imersa em chumbo sólido com os ele- mentos de combustı́vel refrigerados por Hélio. Esta proposta permite a utilização de um ciclo termodinâmico direto (Brayton), que é mais eficiente do que o ciclo a vapor. Estas ideias não violam os conceitos fı́sicos presentes no conceito do EA (Energy Amplifier) e têm vanta- gens evidentes na redução das exigências do acelerador, sendo mais realista com a tecnologia atual do mesmo. Por fim, a utilização de He como refrigerante, quando comparado com chumbo lı́quido, se aproxima da tecnologia presente nos reatores refrigerados a gás atuais.

LINHA-DE-PESQUISA.TITULO-DA-LINHA-DE-PESQUISA: Simulaes de Monte Carlo e Pentaquark
LINHA-DE-PESQUISA.OBJETIVOS-LINHA-DE-PESQUISA: All known particles can be classified using the constituent quark model, where light mesons are described as bound states of a quark and antiquark pair and baryons as bound states of three quarks. On the other hand, high energy experiments has shown an internal meson and baryon structure much more complex made of sea of quarks, antiquarks and gluons. Saying this, one can expect particles with an internal structure more complex, like for example, 5 quarks states (q-q-q-q-qbar), where the antiquark has a different flavor then the other four. These states constituted of something different of quark-antiquark or three quarks are called exotic states. The idea of exotic particles comes from QCD but experimental results on exotic baryons are surrounded by so much controversy that no strong evidence to make the pentaquark appear in the Particle Data Group was found. However, theorist groups didn?t stop working and based on several models, the existence of exotic particles has been proposed. In 1997, Diakonov, Petrov and Polyakov, based on Chiral Quark-Soliton Model, predicted an antidecuplet, where the lower energy state had a mass of only ~ 1.5 GeV and a width of 25 MeV. This extremely narrow width has stimulated an intense experimental search. In the period between March and July of 2004 new data has been taken using proton and deuteron target specifically for the θ+ research and the possible exited states with ten (10) times more statistic than previous published results. In December of 2004, data was taken for the research of other exotic states predicted by Diakonov, Petrov e Polyakov. From these measurements, cross section upper limits have been extracted for several photoproduction channels and the results have been published.

Nucleon spin structure has been an active, exciting and intriguing subject of interest for the last three decades. Recent precision spin-structure data from Jefferson Lab have significantly advanced our knowledge of nucleon structure in the valence quark (high-x) region and improved our understanding of higher-twist effects, spin sum rules and quark-hadron duality. Among the results one can cite spin sum rules and polarizabilities in the low to intermediate Q2 region and precision measurements of the spin asymmetry, A1, in the highs' region, the up and down quark spin distributions in the nucleon, the second moment of the spin structure functions and the twist-3 matrix element d2 , the comparison between high Q2 and Lattice QCD calculation, resonance spin-structure functions in the intermediate Q2 range, which, in combination with DIS data, enable a detailed study of quark-hadron duality in spin-structure functions. An experiment to study neutron transversity and transverse spin asymmetries is discussed. A future plan with the 12 GeV energy upgrade at JLab is briefly outlined.

LINHA-DE-PESQUISA.TITULO-DA-LINHA-DE-PESQUISA: Fotoproduo de Estranheza e Extrao de Seo de Choque
LINHA-DE-PESQUISA.OBJETIVOS-LINHA-DE-PESQUISA: The huge amount of high quality data acquired during the pentaquark research allowed its utilization to study the strangeness photoproduction reactions. The main motivation is to provide data to investigate the spectrum of non strange baryonic resonances (N* and Δ) above the strangeness production threshold (energy in the Center of Mass W = 1.6 GeV). In the range between threshold and the highest energy from our data (W = 2.9 GeV) the quark models predict several baryonic resonances, but very few were established. This is the so called "missing resonance" problem. Many baryon resonances were predicted studying the channels with pions. They are very broad and overlapping, making partial analysis difficult. It is important to provide data to investigate the spectrum of baryon resonances, with the decay in KY (Y = \Lambda or Σ). Although the branching fractions of most resonances to KY final states are small compared to 3-body modes there are some advantages: 1) more often 2-body final states are easier to analyze than 3-body system states, and 2) couplings of nucleon resonances to KY final states will differ from the \piN, ηN and \pi\piN final states. The goals of this work are to analyze the \gamma n(p) -> K+ \Sigma-(p) channel to study the baryon resonances not otherwise revealed and obtain information about couplings of nucleon resonances to KY final states. The \gamma n(p) -> K+ \Sigma- (p) differential cross section has been extracted with the CLAS large acceptance spectrometer at the Jefferson lab Hall-B, over a wide range of kaon scattering angles (10 and 140) using g10 deuterium data taken with low and high torus field and a tagged photon beam in the energy range from 1.0 up to 3.6 GeV. There are almost no experimental data on neutrons and the study of such reaction channel using the CLAS g10 data will give a set of results in gamma-neutron interactions in a wide Eγ and angular range.
